There are a few ways to change the color of a span tag on mouse over. One way is to use CSS. You can add a class to the span tag and then use CSS to change the color of the span tag when the mouse is over it.

Here is an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.red-text {
  color: red;
}

.red-text:hover {
  color: blue;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<span class="red-text">This text is red.</span>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the span tag has a class of "red-text". When the mouse is over the span tag, the color is changed to blue.

Another way to change the color of a span tag on mouse over is to use JavaScript. You can add an onmouseover and onmouseout event to the span tag and then change the color of the span tag using JavaScript.

Here is an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.red-text {
  color: red;
}

.red-text:hover {
  color: blue;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<span class="red-text" id="mySpan">This text is red.</span>

<script>
document.getElementById("mySpan").onmouseover = function() {
  this.style.color = "blue";
}

document.getElementById("mySpan").onmouseout = function() {
  this.style.color = "red";
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the onmouseover event is added to the span tag when the page is loaded. When the mouse is over the span tag, the color is changed to blue. When the mouse is out of the span tag, the color is changed back to red.

